    "boxscore_url": "https://www.uabsports.com/sports/baseball/stats/2026/east-carolina/boxscore/22867",
    "recap_url": "https://www.uabsports.com/news/2026/3/20/baseball-uab-falls-on-friday-night-at-east-carolina",
    "recap_headline": "University of Alabama at Birmingham Athletics",
    "recap_text": "GREENVILLE, N.C.\n\u2013 UAB (13-9) fell in a pitchers' duel on Friday night as the Blazers dropped game one of the series with East Carolina (14-8-1), 3-2. The two pitching staffs combined for 16 strikeouts and only four walks were drawn between the two teams.\nBoth sides were scoreless until the top of the third when the Blazers got some offense going. The inning started on a leadoff double by\nBaylor Roberts\n. After a fly ball moved Roberts to third,\nLandon Beaver\nhit a sac fly to bring Roberts home to give UAB a 1-0 lead.\nThe Pirates answered in the bottom half of the third after a leadoff base hit of their own. Davin Whitaker was credited with a leadoff single and Grady Lenahan doubled to put runners on second and third. Braden Burress scored Whitaker on a groundout to short to tie the game at one.\nECU would take the lead with a single tally in the bottom of the fourth. Jack Herring led off the inning with a single and would advance to third on back-to-back wild pitches. Herring would score after a Colby Wallace single on a 3-0 count to give the Pirates a 2-1 lead.\nEast Carolina added an insurance run in the bottom of the seventh. Walker Barron dropped a single into right field to bring around Carlos Jacome to add to the Pirate advantage.\nUAB starting pitcher\nMason Steele\nheld his own through six-plus innings of work on Friday night as he turned in his third straight start of at least six innings pitched. Steele's final line was 6.0+ innings pitched, three runs (all earned), four strikeouts, and no walks on 88 pitches.\nThe Blazers would try to mount a rally in the top of the ninth as the Blazers got three of their first four hitters on in the inning. With the bases loaded,\nKevin Hall Jr.\nwould score on a wild pitch to cut the lead to 3-2, but the comeback would fall short as the Pirates took game one on Friday night.\nNOTES\n- The UAB pitching staff allowed just one walk for the third time this season. The staff allowed three runs or fewer for the seventh time this season, but UAB fell to 6-1 in those games.\n- UAB also fell to 10-1 when scoring first.\n-\nLandon Beaver\nrecorded his sixth multi-hit game of the season. Beaver now has eight hits in his last six games.\n-\nBaylor Roberts\nalso picked up two hits in the game which marked his fourth multi-hit game of the season.\n- Both Roberts and\nBrady Waugh\nextended their respective on-base streaks on Friday night. Waugh now has a 15-game on-base streak while Roberts extended his to 12.\n-\nAlex Dupuy\ntied\nKevin Hall Jr.\nwith his sixth stolen base of the season.\nThe Blazers and Pirates will square off in the middle game of the series on Saturday afternoon. First pitch from Clark-LeClair Stadium is slated for 4 p.m. ET/3 p.m. CT on ESPN+.\nFOLLOW THE BLAZERS\nFor more information on the UAB Baseball team, follow @UAB_Baseball on X and Instagram.\nCompetitive Excellence Fund\nIn the current landscape of college athletics, the Competitive Excellence Fund has become integral in our department's mission to Win Champions, Graduate with Honors, and Impact the community. Through your generosity, our coaches will have the greatest opportunity to recruit, retain, and resource talented student athletes worthy of wearing a UAB uniform.\nClick here\nor connect with Blazer Boosters on how you can continue to fuel success.",
